{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}} {{Infobox military conflict |image=The Fight at Seven Oaks.jpg |image_size=300px |caption=The Fight at Seven Oaks, 19 June 1816 |conflict=Battle of Seven Oaks |partof=The [[Pemmican War]] |date=19 June 1816 |place=Seven Oaks (present day [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]]) |result=Decisive Métis/North West Company victory |combatant1={{flagicon image|Metis Blue.svg}} [[Métis people (Canada)|Métis]] of the [[North West Company]] |combatant2={{flagicon image|Hudson's Bay Company Flag.svg}} [[Hudson's Bay Company]] |commander1={{flagicon image|Metis Blue.svg}} [[Cuthbert Grant]] |commander2={{flagicon image|Hudson's Bay Company Flag.svg}} [[Robert Semple (Canada)|Robert Semple]]{{KIA}} |strength1=65<ref name="Hargrave1871"/> |strength2=28<ref name="Hargrave1871"/> |casualties1=1<ref name="Hargrave1871"/> |casualties2=21<ref name="Hargrave1871"/> {{Designation list |embed=yes |designation1=NHSC |designation1_offname=Battle of Seven Oaks National Historic Site of Canada |designation1_date=1920 }} |}} The '''Battle of Seven Oaks'''<ref>Also known as the '''Seven Oaks Massacre''' and the '''Seven Oaks Incident'''.</ref> was a violent confrontation in what was known as the [[Pemmican War]] between the [[Hudson's Bay Company]] (HBC) and the [[North West Company]] (NWC), rivals in the [[fur trade]], that took place on 19 June 1816. It was the climax of a long dispute in western [[Canada]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |first=J.E. |last=Rea |date=4 March 2015 |url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/articles/seven-oaks-incident |title=Seven Oaks Incident |work=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]] |publisher=[[Historica Canada]] |edition=online |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120616121234/http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/articles/seven-oaks-incident |archivedate=16 June 2012 |df= }}</ref> The [[Métis people (Canada)|Métis people]], who fought for the North West Company, called it "the Victory of Frog Plain" (''la Victoire de la Grenouillère'')<ref> Barkwell, Lawrence. "Battle of Seven Oaks". The Canadian Encyclopedia, 24 July 2018, Historica Canada. https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/seven-oaks-incident. Accessed 08 October 2018.</ref>.
==Background== In 1814, [[Miles MacDonell]], Governor of the [[Red River Colony]] (the area around present-day [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]]), issued the [[Pemmican Proclamation]],<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |first=John E. |last=Foster |date=24 July 2015 |url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/articles/pemmican-proclamation |title=Pemmican Proclamation |work=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]] |publisher=[[Historica Canada]] |edition=online |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120430013310/http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/articles/pemmican-proclamation |archivedate=30 April 2012 |df= }}</ref> which prohibited the export of [[pemmican]] from the colony for the next year. It was meant to guarantee adequate supplies for the Hudson's Bay Colony, but it was viewed by the North West Company as a ploy by employees of the [[Thomas Douglas, 5th Earl of Selkirk|Earl of Selkirk]] (majority shareholder of the Hudson's Bay Company) to monopolize the foodstuff, which was important to the North West Company.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bumsted|first1=J.M.|title=Lord Selkirk: a life|date=2008|publisher=University of Manitoba Press|isbn=9780887553370|page=236}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/macdonell_miles_6E.html|work=Dictionary of Canadian Biography|title=MacDonell, Miles|author=Mays, Herbert|publisher=University of Toronto/Université Laval|year=1987}}</ref>
The local [[Métis people (Canada)|Métis]] did not acknowledge the authority of the Red River Settlement, and this stand was probably consistent with the [[Royal Proclamation of 1763]]. The Pemmican Proclamation was a blow to both the Métis and North West Company. The North West Company accused the HBC of unfairly monopolizing the fur trade by this edict. As the North West Company floundered under these and other restrictions, the HBC attempted to take it over, but was not successful.{{citation needed |date = June 2012}}
Later in 1815, after several conflicts and suffering from "severe emotional instability",<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |first=J.M. |last=Bumsted |date=17 November 2014 |url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/articles/miles-macdonell |title=Miles MacDonnell |work=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]] |publisher=[[Historica Canada]] |edition=online |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120920041320/http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/articles/miles-macdonell |archivedate=20 September 2012 |df= }}</ref> MacDonnell resigned as governor of the [[Red River Colony]]. He was replaced by [[Robert Semple (Canada)|Robert Semple]], an American businessman with no previous experience in the [[fur trade]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |first=J.E. |last=Rea |date=17 November 2014 |url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/articles/robert-semple |title=Robert Semple |work=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]] |publisher=[[Historica Canada]] |edition=online |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120920041326/http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/articles/robert-semple |archivedate=20 September 2012 |df= }}</ref>
==Battle== [[File:Cuthbert Grant.jpg|thumb|upright|left|In 1816, [[Cuthbert Grant]] led a band of [[North West Company]] employees to seize a supply of [[pemmican]] from the [[Hudson's Bay Company]].]] In 1816 a band of mostly Métis which included some French-Canadians, English, and Indigenous employees working for the North West Company, led by [[Cuthbert Grant]], seized a supply of pemmican from the Hudson's Bay Company, which previously had been stolen from the Métis.<ref>{{cite book |title=Report of the proceedings connected with the disputes between the Earl of Selkirk and the North West Company: at the assizes, held at York, in Upper Canada, October&nbsp;1818 |publisher=James Lane and Nahum Mower |year=1819 |location=Montreal, Quebec}}</ref> They were travelling to meet traders of the North West Company, to whom they intended to sell it.
They encountered Semple and a group of HBC men and settlers north of [[Fort Douglas (Canada)|Fort Douglas]] along the [[Red River of the North|Red River]] at a location known to the English as Seven Oaks, and called ''la Grenouillière'' (Frog Plain) by the Métis. The North West Company sent a French-Canadian, François-Firmin Boucher, to speak to Semple's men. He and Semple argued, and a gunfight ensued when the English tried to arrest Boucher and seize his horse.<ref name=Narratives_1819>{{cite book |title=Narratives of John Pritchard, Pierre Chrysologue Pambrun, and Frederick Damien Heurter, respecting the aggressions of the North-West Company, against the Earl of Selkirk's settlement upon Red River |publisher=John Murray |location=London, England |year=1819}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |first=François-Firmin |last=Boucher |title=François-Firmin Boucher à ses Concitoyens |trans-title=François-Firmin Boucher to his Countrymen |publisher=author-published |year=c. 1819}}</ref> Although early reports said that the Métis fired the first shot and began the fray, the Royal Commissioner W.B. Coltman determined with "next to certainty" that it was one of Semple's men who fired first.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Metis: Memorable Events and Memorable Personalities |author-link1=George R. D. Goulet |first1=George |last1=Goulet |first2=Terry |last2=Goulet |year=2006 |ISBN=978-1-894638-98-2}}</ref> <ref>Barkwell, Lawrence. "Battle of Seven Oaks". The Canadian Encyclopedia, 24 July 2018, Historica Canada. https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/seven-oaks-incident. Accessed 08 October 2018.</ref>The Métis were skilled sharpshooters and outnumbered Semple's forces by nearly 3&nbsp;to&nbsp;1. They repulsed the attack, killing 21&nbsp;men, including Governor Semple, while suffering only one fatality, Joseph Letendre dit Battosh the 16&nbsp;year-old son of Jean Baptiste Letendre.<ref name="Hargrave1871">{{cite book |first=Joseph James |last=Hargrave |title=Red River |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p3yHV0tF9REC |year=1871 |publisher=author-published |page=487}}</ref> [[Pierre Falcon]], a Métis poet, later celebrated the victory of the Métis in his song "La Chanson de la Grenouillère".<ref name="Hargrave1871"/><ref>{{cite web |title=La chanson des Bois-Brûlés |work=S.H.S.B. |publisher=Centre du patrimoine |location=Saint-Boniface, Manitoba |accessdate=11 January 2014 |url =http://shsb.mb.ca/node/374}}</ref>
==Aftermath== [[File:Battle of Seven Oaks Monument3.jpg|thumb|An obelisk monument to commemorate the battle was erected in 1891 at [[West Kildonan, Winnipeg|West Kildonan]], a suburban neighbourhood of [[Winnipeg]].]] On the day after the battle, the settlers, demoralized from the losses, quickly gathered their belongings and prepared to leave the colony. On the next day, they set sail northward, leaving the Métis in command of the settlement.<ref>{{cite book |last=Friesen |first=Gerald |contribution=Maintaining the Old Order 1805-1844 |title=The Canadian Prairies a History |page=80 |edition=Student |location=Toronto, ON |publisher=University of Toronto Press |year=1987}}</ref>
The Métis were exonerated by W.B. Coltman, a [[Royal Commission]]er appointed to investigate the incident, but Lord Selkirk attempted to prosecute several members of the North West Company for murder and kept Boucher in prison for nearly two years without specific charges. All trials ended in acquittals, and the remaining charges were dropped. Members of the North West Company counter-sued Selkirk, whose health and influence subsequently declined. Following Selkirk's death in 1820, the two companies merged in 1821. In 1828, Cuthbert Grant was given an annual salary and the position of "warden of the plains of Red River" by the Hudson's Bay Company.<ref>{{DFHD|962|Grant, Cuthbert National Historic Person|9 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite DCB |first=George |last=Woodcock |title=Grant, Cuthbert |volume=8 |accessdate=12 January 2014 |url=http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/grant_cuthbert_1854_8E.html }}</ref>
In 1891, the Manitoba Historical Society erected an obelisk monument commemorating the battle at the intersection of Main Street and Rupertsland Boulevard in the Winnipeg district of [[West Kildonan]], the approximate centre of the battle site. The site was designated a [[National Historic Sites of Canada|National Historic Site of Canada]] in 1920.<ref>{{CRHP|16005|Battle of Seven Oaks|5 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{DFHD|149|Battle of Seven Oaks National Historic Site of Canada|8 January 2015}}</ref> The surrounding neighbourhood was named "Seven Oaks" after the battle.{{citation needed|date=June 2012}} As part of Parks Canada reconciliation with the Métis, new interpretive plaques were installed and the Seven Oaks Park was re-landscaped. The site was officially reopened on 19 June 2016, to mark the 200th anniversary of the battle. <ref>https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/seven-oaks-incident</ref>
